{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai\" (chapter 50 of *Diwan-E-Ghalib*) opens with a couplet about the heart's immersion in sorrow.**[^1]\n\nIn translation:  \n\"This weak, failed heart's capacity for pain is more than enough;  \nThe grief that rose-red wine is on the wane is more than enough.\"[^2]\n\nThe opening evokes the heart (*dil*) as weak and unsuccessful (*boda dil-e-nakaam*), dwelling in the \"house of grief\" (*gham khaane mein*), with an overflowing capacity for sorrow (*bahut hai*), even as rose-red wine (*mai-e-gulfaam*)—symbolizing fleeting joys or intoxications—dwindles.[^3]\n\nIn transliteration:  \n\"Gham khaane mein boda dil-e-nakaam bahut hai  \nYeh ranj ke kam hai mai-e-gulfaam bahut hai\"[^4]\n\nIn the original Urdu:  \n\"غم کھانے میں بودا دل_ناکام بہت ہے  \nیہ رنج کہ کم ہے مئے_گلفام بہت ہے\"[^5]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/translation/#p-b39b6a).\n[^3]: Ibid.\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/transliteration/#p-d3a1ee).\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/50-gham-khaane-mein-boda-dil-e-nakaam-bahut-hai/original/#p-a0be2a).",
